text=>>comment%3c%3c%0aSummary:some caveats about using the MBTI%0aParent:(Consulting.)ChangeManagement%0aIncludeMe:[[(Consulting.)ChangeManagement]]%0aCategories:[[!Articles]]%0aTags: mbti%0a(:tags-hide mbti :)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a[[#excerpt]]%0aThis is some material from a colleague on the dangers of using the MBTI to stereotype or type cast people. If you are a user of these tools, please read this and incorporate it into your practice. This isn't an attempt to disuade you from using the MBTI (I still use it quite often) but to be wary of it. Remeber: "The Map is Not the Territory!"%0a[[#excerptend]]%0a%0a!! MBTI Research--The Untold Story%0a%0a%0aEach year, hundreds of people every year invest about a thousand%0adollars and a week's time to learn how to use the Myers-Briggs Type%0aIndicator (MBTI) in training programs. In addition, over a million of%0aother people attend these programs or are subjected to this popular%0apersonality test. While most psychologists consider the MBTI to be%0aunreliable and inconsistent with current scientific theory, the%0ageneral public has no knowledge of its weaknesses. They do not%0aappreciate the dangers of typing, and they do not have access to the%0ascientific literature that has discredited it. You may be interested%0ain finding out about the research that MBTI trainers do not%0amention--indeed, may not even know about. %0a%0a!! Sipps, Gary J., Ralph A. Alexander and Larry Friedt. "Item Analysis of the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator." Educational and Psychological Measurement, 45 (1985), 789-796.%0a%0aThe only published item-factor analysis of the MBTI, this study%0aexamined a diverse population of 1,291 subjects. The findings%0arevealed that 41 of the 95 items (43%25) did not correlate significantly%0awith the factors they were supposed to measure. The failure rate was%0aas follows: E-I, 27.3%25; S-N, 57.7%25; T-F, 56.5%25; and J-P, 29.2%25. "This%0araises the question of the appropriateness of the use of these items%0aon the questionnaire," the researchers concluded. %0a%0a!! Carlyn, M. "An Assessment of the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator." Journal of Personal Assessment, 41 (1977), 461-473.%0a%0aCarlyn analyzed the independence of the four scales of the MBTI and%0afound that the fourth scale, judgment-perception (J-P), had an%0aunexpectedly high relationship to the sensing-intuition (S-N), with%0acorrelations ranging from .23 to .48 in 11 samples. People who scored%0ahigh in sensing (S) tended to score high in judgment (J); and people%0awho scored high in intuition (N) tended to score high in perception%0a(P). This finding discredits the J-P scale, which is not one of the%0aoriginal Jungian dimensions. Carlyn's findings replicated those of%0aStrickler and Ross (1964). %0a%0a!! Strickler, L. J. and J. A. Ross. "Some Correlates of a Jungian Personality Inventory." Psychological Reports, 14 (April 1964), 623-643.%0a%0aThis study showed unexpectedly high correlations between the S-N scale%0aand the P-J scale.%0a%0a!! McCarley, N. and T. G. Carskadon. "Test-retest Reliabilities of Scales and Subscales of the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator and of Criteria for Clinical Interpretive Hypotheses Involving Them." Research in Psychological Type, 6 (1983), 24-36.%0a%0aAssigning a type is the primary objective of the MBTI. This study%0aevaluated the stability of the type designation. It noted that the%0atype designation of 53%25 of the subjects changed when retested after%0afive weeks. %0a%0a!! Loomis, Mary and June Singer. "Testing the Bipolar Assumption in Jung's Typology." Journal of Analytical Psychology, 25 (1980), 351-356.%0a%0aTwo Jungian analysts tested the stability of the MBTI type%0adesignations by comparing the types produced by the MBTI, which uses a%0aforced-choice psychometric, and the types produced by a modified MBTI,%0awhich used the same 95 items with scaled responses. If the types%0aproduced by the MBTI are not artificial by-products of the%0aforced-choice questioning method, then changing the method should not%0achange the type designations. In a sample of 79 subjects, 46%25 of the%0atype designations changed when the scaled version was given. They%0aconcluded that the forced-choice questioning method used by the MBTI%0ais not a sufficiently exact measuring device. %0a%0a!! Druckman, Daniel and Robert A. Bjork, eds. The Mind's Eye: Enhancing Human Performance. Washington, DC: National Academy Press, 1991.%0a%0aThe authors summarized studies that evaluated the MBTI and drew%0aseveral conclusions: %0a%0a"The evidence summarized in this section raises questions about the%0avalidity of the MBTI. . . . Unfortunately, neither the gains in%0asensitivity nor the impact of those gains on performance have been%0adocumented by research. Nor has the instrument been validated in a%0along-term study of successful and unsuccessful careers. Lacking such%0aevidence, it is a curiosity why the instrument is used so widely,%0aparticularly in large organizations." (p. 99) %0a%0a"The lack of a supportive research foundation for the MBTI leads the%0acommittee to recommend that the instrument not be used in career%0acounseling programs until its validity is supported by research." (p. 100) %0a%0a"The popularity of this instrument in the absence of proven scientific%0aworth is troublesome." (p. 101) %0a%0a!! Jung, C. G. Psychological Types. Princeton, NJ: Princeton University Press, 1971 (1921).%0a%0aWhen you read what Carl Jung had to say in Psychological Types, you%0adiscover that it his views are not the same as those of MBTI%0aproponents. %0a%0aIn speaking of the opposing factors of his typology, Jung wrote:%0a"Every human being possesses both mechanisms as an expression of his%0anatural life-rhythm. . . . one mechanism will naturally predominate,%0aand if this condition becomes in any way chronic a type will be%0aproduced. . . . Hence there can never be a pure type in the sense that%0ait possesses only one mechanism with the complete atrophy of the%0aother." pp. 5-6. %0a%0aIn other words, Jung used the concept of "type" to represent an%0aextreme, chronic or pathological condition. He saw the larger%0apopulation of ordinary, healthy people as being outside the boundaries%0aof his typology. He later articulated this view when speaking about%0aextraverts and introverts. "There is, finally, a third group, and here%0ait is hard to say whether the motivation comes chiefly from within or%0awithout. This group is the most numerous and includes the less%0adifferentiated normal man, who is considered normal either because he%0aallows himself no excesses or because he has no need of them. The%0anormal man is by definition, influenced as much from within as from%0awithout." pp. 515-516 (1923). %0a%0aAccording to Jung's thinking, it is erroneous to say that a person is%0aeither an introvert or an extrovert. "By comparing many such cases it%0agradually became clear to me that there must be two fundamentally%0adifferent general attitudes which would divide human beings into two%0agroups--provided the whole of humanity consisted of highly%0adifferentiated individuals. . . . this is obviously not the case." (p. 549 (1936). %0a%0aHe disagreed with the practice of typing people. "The opinion has got%0aabout that my method of treatment consists in fitting patients into%0athis system and giving them corresponding 'advice.' This regrettable%0amisunderstanding completely ignores the fact that this kind of%0aclassification is nothing but a childish parlour game, every bit as%0afutile as the division of mankind into brachycephalics and%0adolichocephalics. My typology is far rather a critical apparatus%0aserving to sort out and organize the welter of empirical material, but%0anot in any sense to stick labels on people." p. xiv (1934).%0a
