 was%0a%3c as follows: E-I, 27.3%25; S-N, 57.7%25; T-F, 56.5%25; and J-P, 29.2%25. "This%0a%3c raises the question of the appropriateness of the use of these items%0a%3c on the questionnaire," the researchers concluded. %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Carlyn, M. "An Assessment of the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator." Journal of Personal Assessment, 41 (1977), 461-473.%0a%3c %0a%3c Carlyn analyzed the independence of the four scales of the MBTI and%0a%3c found that the fourth scale, judgment-perception (J-P), had an%0a%3c unexpectedly high relationship to the sensing-intuition (S-N), with%0a%3c correlations ranging from .23 to .48 in 11 samples. People who scored%0a%3c high in sensing (S) tended to score high in judgment (J); and people%0a%3c who scored high in intuition (N) tended to score high in perception%0a%3c (P). This finding discredits the J-P scale, which is not one of the%0a%3c original Jungian dimensions. Carlyn's findings replicated those of%0a%3c Strickler and Ross (1964). %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Strickler, L. J. and J. A. Ross. "Some Correlates of a Jungian Personality Inventory." Psychological Reports, 14 (April 1964), 623-643.%0a%3c %0a%3c This study showed unexpectedly high correlations between the S-N scale%0a%3c and the P-J scale.%0a%3c %0a%3c !! McCarley, N. and T. G. Carskadon. "Test-retest Reliabilities of Scales and Subscales of the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator and of Criteria for Clinical Interpretive Hypotheses Involving Them." Research in Psychological Type, 6 (1983), 24-36.%0a%3c %0a%3c Assigning a type is the primary objective of the MBTI. This study%0a%3c evaluated the stability of the type designation. It noted that the%0a%3c type designation of 53%25 of the subjects changed when retested after%0a%3c five weeks. %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Loomis, Mary and June Singer. "Testing the Bipolar Assumption in Jung's Typology." Journal of Analytical Psychology, 25 (1980), 351-356.%0a%3c %0a%3c Two Jungian analysts tested the stability of the MBTI type%0a%3c designations by comparing the types produced by the MBTI, which uses a%0a%3c forced-choice psychometric, and the types produced by a modified MBTI,%0a%3c which used the same 95 items with scaled responses. If the types%0a%3c produced by the MBTI are not artificial by-products of the%0a%3c forced-choice questioning method, then changing the method should not%0a%3c change the type designations. In a sample of 79 subjects, 46%25 of the%0a%3c type designations changed when the scaled version was given. They%0a%3c concluded that the forced-choice questioning method used by the MBTI%0a%3c is not a sufficiently exact measuring device. %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Druckman, Daniel and Robert A. Bjork, eds. The Mind's Eye: Enhancing Human Performance. Washington, DC: National Academy Press, 1991.%0a%3c %0a%3c The authors summarized studies that evaluated the MBTI and drew%0a%3c several conclusions: %0a%3c %0a%3c "The evidence summarized in this section raises questions about the%0a%3c validity of the MBTI. . . . Unfortunately, neither the gains in%0a%3c sensitivity nor the impact of those gains on performance have been%0a%3c documented by research. Nor has the instrument been validated in a%0a%3c long-term study of successful and unsuccessful careers. Lacking such%0a%3c evidence, it is a curiosity why the instrument is used so widely,%0a%3c particularly in large organizations." (p. 99) %0a%3c %0a%3c "The lack of a supportive research foundation for the MBTI leads the%0a%3c committee to recommend that the instrument not be used in career%0a%3c counseling programs until its validity is supported by research." (p. 100) %0a%3c %0a%3c "The popularity of this instrument in the absence of proven scientific%0a%3c worth is troublesome." (p. 101) %0a%3c %0a%3c !! Jung, C. G. Psychological Types. Princeton, NJ: Princeton University Press, 1971 (1921).%0a%3c %0a%3c When you read what Carl Jung had to say in Psychological Types, you%0a%3c discover that it his views are not the same as those of MBTI%0a%3c proponents. %0a%3c %0a%3c In speaking of the opposing factors of his typology, Jung wrote:%0a%3c "Every human being possesses both mechanisms as an expression of his%0a%3c natural life-rhythm. . . . one mechanism will naturally predominate,%0a%3c and if this condition becomes in any way chronic a type will be%0a%3c produced. . . . Hence there can never be a pure type in the sense that%0a%3c it possesses only one mechanism with the complete atrophy of the%0a%3c other." pp. 5-6. %0a%3c %0a%3c In other words, Jung used the concept of "type" to represent an%0a%3c extreme, chronic or pathological condition. He saw the larger%0a%3c population of ordinary, healthy people as being outside the boundaries%0a%3c of his typology. He later articulated this view when speaking about%0a%3c extraverts and introverts. "There is, finally, a third group, and here%0a%3c it is hard to say whether the motivation comes chiefly from within or%0a%3c without. This group is the most numerous and includes the less%0a%3c differentiated normal man, who is considered normal either because he%0a%3c allows himself no excesses or because he has no need of them. The%0a%3c normal man is by definition, influenced as much from within as from%0a%3c without." pp. 515-516 (1923). %0a%3c %0a%3c According to Jung's thinking, it is erroneous to say that a person is%0a%3c either an introvert or an extrovert. "By comparing many such cases it%0a%3c gradually became clear to me that there must be two fundamentally%0a%3c different general attitudes which would divide human beings into two%0a%3c groups--provided the whole of humanity consisted of highly%0a%3c differentiated individuals. . . . this is obviously not the case." (p. 549 (1936). %0a%3c %0a%3c He disagreed with the practice of typing people. "The opinion has got%0a%3c about that my method of treatment consists in fitting patients into%0a%3c this system and giving them corresponding 'advice.' This regrettable%0a%3c misunderstanding completely ignores the fact that this kind of%0a%3c classification is nothing but a childish parlour game, every bit as%0a%3c futile as the division of mankind into brachycephalics and%0a%3c dolichocephalics. My typology is far rather a critical apparatus%0a%3c serving to sort out and organize the welter of empirical material, but%0a%3c not in any sense to stick labels on people." p. xiv (1934).%0a
